Youths will benefit from about 280,000 new jobs which the state is targeting to create through a Sh15.59 billion ($150 million) loan from the World Bank in the next five years, the Public service, Youth and Gender affairs ministry has said.This follows the launch of the National steering committee that will oversee the implementation of the Kenya Youth Employment and Opportunities formed in 2010.&ldquo;The employment opportunities will directly benefit jobless youths. The main element of the KYEOP include training in industrial related skills and start-up grants to support business development,&rdquo; Cabinet Secretary Sicily Kariuki said yesterday at a media briefing.She said the National Industrial Training Authority, Micro and Small Enterprises, Ministry of East African Community Affairs and the Ministry of Public Service and Gender will work together on the project.